Two years ago AUTOPHOBIA was my last project before the pandemic - Directed by @peter.garajszki Co-Written with the help of Alexa Dobre an academic writer and own experiences of psychotherapy, this film is an attempt to raise awareness of ourselves to ourselves mixing science with aesthetics. - @peter.garajszki

Assholes (2017) ➡️ 4/10
Still wanna marry Peter Vack tho.
But about this nonsense, let me quote IndieWire:

"Peter Vack’s Directorial Debut Is One of the Most Disgusting Movies Ever Made

Unfolding like a microbudget cross between “Salò, or the 120 Days of Sodom” and “The Squid and the Whale,” Peter Vack’s impressively disgusting “Assholes” is the kind of movie that you wish you could unsee, one you have to watch in your peripheral vision because straight-on viewing would be way too nauseating.

It starts off seeming so much more benign. The film might end on a comedic note of Cronenbergian body horror, but it begins by exhuming the desiccated corpse of the mumblecore movement. A scrappy 30-year-old New Yorker who’s parlayed his model good looks and outré sensibilities into a career as the indie film world’s most visible overlooked actor, Vack has starred in so many films about solipsistic young people shouting at each other that it’s natural to assume his directorial debut would be cut from the same cloth. And then we learn that the title is a double entendre."

Crumb (1994) ➡️ 8,5/10
Kind of a shame i haven't seen this movie until now. Terry Zwigoff's documentary about Robert Crumb, a really controversial (mostly due to his recurring themes of graphic sexual and violent abuse of women) but famous (or infamous) cartoonist. It basically portrays a creative and really prolific mind of someone who's clearly making art "inspired" by his PTSD. Crumb is without a question a perverted freak, who grew up in a really gloomy family with 2 brothers. Both of them are pretty damaged and are struggling with cumulative mental illnesses in their own way. The one who was still living with his mother fully antisocially during the shooting was actual even more talented than Robert - even pushing him more and more into success - but success avoided him. He killed himself one year after the documentary came out. Robert on the other hand still lives in a small village in southern France after he left the USA and its whole "bullshit" behind him. He married twice, his daughter also became a cartoonist like his wife, his son died in a car accident a few years ago.

Some Kind of Heaven (2020) ➡️ 8,5/10
I got so engaged at the very first moment of this documentary directed by Lance Oppenheim, produced by Darren Aronofsky and also (fun fact) Jeffrey Soros, nephew of George Soros. I can get really excited when a documentary doesn't look like shit just because it's a documentary. It's beautifully photographed and really entertaining. The topic is as surreal as it sounds: the biggest retirement community in Florida called "The Villages" with 130 000 "citizens" living the time of (the dawn of) their lives. I've been once to Florida and I enjoy the whole aesthetics and visual culture attached to it so i'm always pleased to watch movies that were shot there and can capture that atmosphere. Oppenheim didn't make a movie about the whole history of this weird community, although we get to know that this Disney Land for pensioners - or how some of them call it: "God's waiting room for heaven" - was created for Baby Boomers in the concept of making them feel nostalgia and peace in a bubble far from every inconveniences. Meaning: The Villages has its own Newspaper and TV News where the most important piece of news is that a citizen bought a new red roadster after years of driving a family car. The town was designed in a way to make them feel home -  meaning where they were born. Oppenheim takes us to a journey with 4 different individuals living there, searching for solace and emotional security. A married couple, a widow, and a kinda fuckboy (let's call him fuckgentleman since he is like 80) living in a van searching for a nice bimbo preferably with money and a house in The Villages. I didn't really think this topic can have such an effect on me as it did, but one can never know. I had a great time and my eyes were also entertained throughout the movie. Watch it.

Beginning (2020)➡️ 9/10
Incredible, 'too good to be a first feature' from Georgian writer/director Dea Kulumbegashvili. Part of official selection of Cannes 2020. Pins you down to the chair, every arranged, static frame is a fucking painting. The irredundant sounds coming outside of the frames give additional meaning and value throughout the film. A movie about hypocrisy, blind fanaticism, and a woman's journey to despair and the feeling of a worthlessness prey in a community where they are preaching about divine loyalty, sins and consequences of them, but are being immune to actual sins and intimidation, violance and torture. Mindblowingly beautiful laceration. Oh, and music: Nicholas Jaar.

Pieces of a Woman (2020)➡️ 7,5/10
Mundruczó új filmjét meg kell nézni mondjuk azért, mert nagyon-nagyon jó a casting, a forgatókönyv első fele - mielőtt elkezd nagyon sok lenni a szájbarágós metafora (kókadt növények, tiszta víz a pohárba, kopott körömlakk) - és a fényképezés is. Illetve magyar rendező, magyar forgatókönyvíró, úgyhogy a gyengeségei ellenére is büszkeséggel tölt el. Te is úgy legyél magyar, hogy például ezt megnézed! A casting tényleg mesteri, számomra nagyon fontos és kedves színészek kaptak szerepet. Peldául Benny Safdie (ezt nem is kell részleteznem szerintem 🖤), Jimmie Fails a Last Black Man of San Fransiscoból, Molly Parker a Madeline's Madeline-ból (illetve a House of cardsból, de inkább nézzétek meg a Madeline's Madeline-t), Sarah Snook a Successionből. Vanessa Kirby szerintem csodálatos és nagyon hiteles végig, Shia meg Shia, úgyhogy az nem is kérdés.

Never Rarely Sometimes Always (2020)➡️ 7,5/10
Eliza Hittman's new movie set mostly in New York is available for all the anxiety-seekers out there. The title is expressive, the mood is oppressing. It's a worthy continuation of her life's work. In case you haven't seen her two other features yet, it's the perfect time to do so. 'It felt like love' (2013) was her remarkable debut in which she managed to develop an unmistakeably recognizable style. In 'Beach rats' (2017), my personal favourite she managed to take it next level.

The Pleasure of Being Robbed (2008) ➡️7/10
I'll always be partial to the genius of the Safdie brothers, hence the 7 points. But also I so fucking love to realise these little things how the girl's character in the movie can be a New Yorkish, modern interpretation of Anna Karina'a character in most of Godard's movies. The red cardigan, the robbery theme. Reminded me of Bande á part from Godard. I am so curious if this was intentional from Josh Safdie in his Cannes debut in 2008's Director's Fortnight. I still don't have his phone number to ask it, but I'll never give up.
Also the protagonist, Eleonore - played by Eleonore Hendricks - was in Chloe Sevigny's short from this year, White Echo. I posted that too last week.

Olla (2019)➡️ 7,5/10
The actress and now also director Ariane Labed (might be known from The Lobster) is Yorgos Lanthimos' wife and creative partner. Her directorial debut (premiered in Cannes last year in Directors' Fortnight) definitely shows the effects of working together with Lanthimos for years. In other words she is also good in this so-called Greek Weird Wave. (tho she's french) The awkwardness, the wide shots, the burnt-orange coloring, the Greek Chorus, or 'What is love' used as the only music throughout the movie. A lot of the camera movements reminded me of Lanthimos' last short with Matt Dillon, 'Nimic'. The narrative itself isnt the strongest one, but Romanna Lobach brings the most out of the script with her genius performance, it's good to know that she is going to be seen in Joanna Hogg's next movie, the sequel of 'The Souvenir'. #mindennapegyfilm #onemovieaday #greekweirdwave #arianelabed #romannalobach #balthazarlab #short #shortfilm #cannes #cannesfilmfestival #directorsfortnight #yorgoslanthimos #movie #quarantinetime #whattowatch #watchmovies #cinematography #movieframes #frames #quarantine

Playtime (1967)➡️ 8/10
Jacques Tati's movie is exceptional from so many aspects. It resonates with writings of the Situationist International movement's avant-garde authors and intellectuals. It shows the dark side of monotony and automatisation caused by capitalism, and the alienating impact of technology. It merges comedy gags with social commentary. It reacts to the political effects on urbanisation during the de Gaulle regime and it predicted (in a symbolic way) the happenings of '68 May in Paris, the student riots. It makes fun of American tourists' approach of the city, but doesnt stop at showing the automatised labyrinth, it also shows a way out of the New Babylon with so clever metaphors. Creating a new harmony, in which people can fulfill their creative potential. It all starts at the Royal Garden, the turning point begins there and after a while we can also hear some guests singing "a la Bastille on aime bien.." in a restaurant named ROYAL garden. :D It encourages the spectators to become actively involved in the happenings, avoids close-ups, so not even Monsieur Hulo (played by Tati himself) becomes a protagonist. It's everyone, or noone. Tati used background noises conceptually, intensifying them rather into foreground noises all along, which brings a great tension throughout the movie. "The film is not about the place we live but about the way we use it."

Unrelated (2007)➡️ 5,5/10
I saw Joanna Hogg's latest movie "The Souvenir" starring Tilda Swinton and her daughter Honor Swinton Byrne last year and I really liked it. They play mother and daughter and the movie is about a young film student girl's fraught relationship with a 
charismatic but untrustworthy posh heroin addict man. Classic A24. I really liked it, I think i rated it 8/10. Since then I wanted to check out the writer/director Joanna Hogg's first feature from 2007., 'Unrelated'. It wasn't a big surprise that I'd rather consider it a TV film (Hogg had some experience in television direction). Despite the fact that it wasn't the strongest movie I've ever seen, i went through with it because it is set in Tuscany, Siena, were I spent a lot of time, and also the young Tom Hiddleston was capable to deliver some Call my by your name vibes. The middle-aged protagonist who escapes from her dying relationship to this group holiday (two posh upper-middle-class british families) and tries to feel happiness and excitement again, flirting with a young man (which is rather embarrassing than sexy) is played by Kathryn Worth, and it might be the worst performance I've ever seen, without question. Wasn't WORTH it. PUN INTENDED.
It's really sad tho to see how a middle aged woman is trying to find her place and to choose between the adults' and the teens' company but doesn't really fit anywhere.

Swallow (2020) ➡️ 6,5/10
Gratifying topic photography-wise. So much that I usually felt like it was overshot when it came to perfectly lighted and set-dressed locations. A little less would have been more. The dynamics of the movie were familiar from big classics, like 'Women on the verge of a nervous breakdown', 'Mother', or 'The woman under the influence' but it couldn't really come up to the quality and entertainment level of those ones. Haley Benett, who still looks like the indie version of Jennifer Lawrence plays satisfyingly the oppressed, lonely housewife with a trauma, but overall it hasn't left me mortified, depressed or overwhelmed enough to remember it one year from now. Remarkable shots tho.

Antigone (2019) ➡️ 8/10
Canada's Oscar candidate is (writer/director) Sophie Deraspe's 21st century adaptation of Sophocles' tragedy: Antigone. It is a beautiful and strong movie which presents how a clever, promising, hard-working, ambitious, brave and stubborn teenage girl ("the brain of the family") fights for her refugee family and heritage putting love, morality and divine law over human law. How she is ready to sacrifice anything for her family, how she is driven by unconditional love towards her family no matter what law says. The movie is really powerful and provocative and you won't really be able to forget Nahema Ricci's performance or her eyes as a matter of fact. The transformation of her lead character from a little naive but loving child into a cynical and strong woman, - a Joan of Arc - is maybe a little bit fast but still believable. This film is about inequality, racism (driven by the media and social media), injustice, and alliance but mostly about the question of expedience versus fighting. Beautiful, strong and thought-provoking drama. Period.
(PS.: I am quite sure Colin Stetson was behind the saxophone tunes used during some of the video inserts which btw made the movie even better, obviously.)

Black Bear (2020)➡️ 8/10
Since #onemovieaday is a reeeally subjective project (what else could it be) I'd like to appreciate this film although it might not going to be appreciated so much by critics and large public. Lawrence Michael Levine's third feature as a director, premiered at Sundance is just soooo much what I specifically like. There's a really great and sexual song from Father John Misty I really love (not just one tho) Hollywood Forever Cemetery Sings, which had a video 8 years ago, starring Aubrey Plaza, and it was the first thing that came to my mind when I started to watch this movie. Then the feeling just got stronger that this movie is like someone has finally made a longer version from that, explaining its story more fulfillingly. I don't know if it came up between Levine and Plaza while they were working on the script but i can't really imagine it didn't. Anyway this movie was so satisfying for my taste, it's everything I like, and it is so enjoyable for everyone who has ever worked on a movie set. Sure, it has the insider jokes (roomtone and 'keep rolling' jokes indeed) sure it is meta, it has the indie hipster vibe, but it is more tricky and clever than those ones which made it to Netflix. Aubrey Plaza gives a stunning performance in Black Bear and the DP's work is also remarkable. I could write a lot about the tricky setting, the clever storytelling, the little elements based on the personal experiences of the creators (Levine and Plaza both has filmmaker partners) but it would all be spoilers. Save it, and watch it when it will be available. #mindennapegyfilm #onemovieaday #movie #sundance2020 #sundance #berlinale2020 #berlinale #aubreyplaza #lawrencemichaellevine #sarahgadon #christopherabbott #blackbear

The truth (2019)➡️ 5/10
So sad that after the incredible Shoplifters, Hirokazu Koreeda didn't manage to transfer any strength or slow but powerful human drama from that into his english-language debut with actresses like Catherine Deneuve or Juliette Binoche. I especially like the 'someone's coming home seemingly for a family reunion but rather for a total shitshow' genre, but this was a Hallmark tv film and also a bad kind from those. Must be hard to make family dynamics as authentic on screen as you did once, when it comes to another nation's social characteristics, especially the french people's. I hope Koreeda's next one will be more like his Cannes-winning masterpiece.

Identifying features (2020) ➡️ 7,5
A highly sensitive and thrilling first feature directed by Fernanda Valadez, that crawls under your skin, lets you think you already know what it is all about and surprises you by avoiding every cliché. An interesting perspective that concentrates on the human factor rather than anything else that would attract more attention or could be sold easier. It cleverly keeps its secrets, but you realise eventually, you don't even need or want to know them, so basically helps you to learn paying attention to the important things. It won the audience award and the special jury award - best screenplay at Sundance Film Festival 2020.

The two popes (2019)➡️ 6,5/10
Kicsit felbaszott, amikor láttam, hogy lesz ez a The
Two Popes cimű film és 20 nappal Sorrentino The New pope-jának (amit nagyon remélem, hogy nem fog elbaszni és rossz fajta giccsbe vagy modorosságba átbillenteni Malkovich) premierje előtt fog kijönni így nem kizárólagosan készíthettem elő lelkemet mind Istennek mind Sorrentinonak az ünnepekre. Fernando Meirelles filmje szerencsére teljesen másjellegű, inkább dokumentarista technikájú, bokorból leskelődős, rángatott kamerás, dekomponált képekkel operáló cucc. Amúgy az első fele tök oké. Kedves tanmese a konzervatív és a liberális gondolkodás ütköztetéséről, optimista edukációs próbálkozás egymás meghallgatásának fontosságágáról. Mindkét színész nagyon jó, Hopkins néha hátborzongatóan. Vicci, hogy Jonathan Pryce végre azt játsza, akihez Game of Thrones-os High Sparrowsága óta hasonlítják meme-ek ezrei. Ratzingerrel kapcsolatban hallottam a botrányokrol, bár ezek nincsenek túlságosan kifejtve a filmben (kétszer lenácizzák, egy focidrukker egy kocsmában és egy utca embere a híradóban) Ferenc pápa "kétes" múltjáról, az Argentín katonai diktatúra alatti tevékenységéről (vagy pont hogy nem tevékenységéről) a 70-es évek végén én nem tudtam, mert sosem olvastam ennek utána. Viszont a filmben a visszaemlékezések borzasztóan néznek ki és nagyon lehoznak a végére (néhol fekete-fehér, néhol pedig Terrence Malick Tree of life-jára emlékeztető képekkel) ahol pedig átváltunk teljes Hollywoodi giccsbe. A filmben a biztosra vehető valódi esemény nagyjából a kiindulópont és a végpont, a kettő között egy elképzelt tanmese áll, de egynek elmegy egy tök jó, történelmi jelentőségű sztoriról, amiről azért mindenképpen kellett egy film. #mindennapegyfilm #onemovieaday #fernandomeirelles #movie #antonyhopkins #jonathanpryce #netflix

Az egy dolog, hogy Kantemir Balagov megcsinálta a Tesnotat 26 évesen, aztán a kék őrület helyett idén ezzel a zöld-piros nyomasztással gondolt előrukkolni, 28 évesen. Nem tudom hogy lehet valakinek ilyen lelkivilága ebben a korban, de elképesztő. Egyébkent Leningrad, 1945, a háborútól mind fizikailag mind mentálisan megnyomorodott emberek. A nézése közben levegőt venni is kellemetlen érzés, remek választás az ünnepekre. 🙃 És zöld és piros és narancs és orosz, mint az állat.

Na tessék itt egy sci-fi, ami tele van ötletekkel, amik bár nem meghökkentően egyediek, mégis alapját képezik annak, hogy jó legyen egy film ebben a műfajban. A baj csak az, hogy mivel svéd (illetve dán) alkotás, oly mértékben nyomasztó, hogy a végére már teljesen kifáraszt (még engem is, aki nyomasztás- párti) illetve az alacsony költségvetés miatt kissé fapados látvány sem tud nem zavarni. Persze a fejlett és klímatudatos északiaknak nyilvánvalóan az edukáció a prioritás, a kiindulási pontunk tehát a klímakatasztrófa után élhetetlenné vált Földről a Marsra emigráló emberek alapvetően 3-4 hetesre tervezett utazása. Az igazi para viszont csak ekkor kezdődik, és nincs is nagyon leszállás a nyomasztás vonatról a végállomásig. A film gondoskodik róla, hogy egy pillanatig se gondoljuk, hogy a romlott, értetlen, szararcú emberi faj tanulna valaha is bármiből és nem a legkárosabb élősködő teremtmény lenne a világon. Nyilván kevesebb a fancy űrjelenet mutogatás és több a studiojelenet és a művészfilmeskedés (néhol picit random túlzásokkal), de az ötlet és a narratíva teljesen oké és érdekes. Egyébként annyira cuki, ahogy a svédek a legapróbb részletekig figyelnek az etnikai/szexuális orientációs/vallási/társadalmi státuszt érintő diverzitásra egy filmen belül. Klímaszorongással vegyített klausztrofóbiában szenvedőknek nem ajánlom.

Karlovy Vary, East of the West szekció, ukrán nevezés. Antonio Lukich első nagyjátékfilmje. Megkapta, hogy hasonlít Reisz Gábor filmjeire, különösen a VAN-ra az alkotás, de én elhiszem Lukich-nak, hogy nem látta. Már csak az övtáskája miatt is, amivel felszerelkezve állt Karlovy Varyban, a vetítésén. Kedves, humoros, de belülről kapirgál a szomorúsága közben. A karakterek nagyon jók. Csak itt szerencsére az azokat megtestesítő színészek is. Kárpátalja, sok-sok magyar vonatkozás. (Egy egészen meglepővel nyit a film egyébként). Nem fájt semmi igazából, nekem nem döcögött a dramaturgia, az anya-fiú kapcsolat konkrétan hibátlanul van elmesélve, minden ízében. A stílusok keverése, a random videoklip szerű, témából, helyszínből adódóan leginkább Simian Mobile Disco - I belive szerű betétek is jókor adtak egy kis levegőt. Megmaradtak a fejemben a kedvenc képeim és a mondanivaló sem ragadt le a nyugatra vágyódás, a generációs gapek és teljes nihill Bermuda-háromszögnél. Tetszett.

Cold war (2018) 10/10
A lassan két éve tartó #mindennapegyfilm - et idén egy újabb 10/10-es példannyal zárhatom, yeah. Ez egy csodálatos film. Manapsag, amikor az a hozzáállás, hogy minimum ket órás mozikat készit mindenki, hogy az az elvárt mértékben behúzza a nézőt, itt van ez a másfél órás ízig-vérig európai csoda. Tiszta történetvezetés, semmi öncélú időhúzás, egy húsig hatoló korrajz, ami meg tudja lépni azt, hogy minden  kérdést feltesz, ami a nagybetűs szerelemben feltevődhet két ember között és meg is válaszolja azokat. Na, ez a nem mindegy. Gyönyörű zenei és képi motívumok kísérik végig vissza-visszatérve, mindig mást jelentve az egyes felvillantott állapotleírásokat, SOSEM feleslegesen vagy just for fun. A karakterek teljesen betalálnak. A L'éclipse (praise Antonioni) nevű helyen egészen meghozza a főszereplő Monica Vitti szerepeit is (véletlen?nem hinném), miközben végig ott van benne a magabiztossággal harcoló önemésztés. A vége is tiszta, a párbeszédek mesterien realisztikusak és jó humorral megírtak. És mindez valószínűsíthetően a rendező (Pawel Pawlikowski) szüleinek története. Kussban néztem végig a stáblistát az utolsó cateringes nevével bezárólag. Egy szebb világban ez nyerné az Oscart, de nem hiszem, hogy van esélye a Roma hype mellett. Pedig pont mindaz van meg benne, ami abból hiányzott.

Nyomozások után a dátumot belőttem, augusztus vége, de semmilyen post nem volt akörül, amiben lehetett volna a szám. És akkor hirtelen beugrott, hogy az Under the Silver Lake volt az. The House That Jack Built 9,5/10 Minimum egyszer újranézős. Olyan volt ez, mint egy Dogma remanifesztum. Egy teljesen tökéletes önigazolás. Minden, Triert nácinak nevező kritikus és filmes arcába bele. Mindezt úgy, hogy Dantét gondolja tovább és miközben minden, ami történik kiszámítható, érzed, hogy amiről szól, és amit mond, az annyira igaz és annyira borzalmas, hogy magadnak sem merted bevallani soha, hogy hasonlóan gondolod, vagy magad sem jöttél még rá. Pedig biztos, ha valaha alkottál vagy akartál alkotni. Ebben a közegben, ami a szemed előtt összeáll 2 és fél óra alatt, eleve értelmezhetetlenné és "földhözragadt" fogalommá alakul maga a nácizmus is. A formai és zenei eklektikát meg csakúgy odaveti mellékesen, hogy ja amúgy nyilván ezt is maxon tudom hozni, hibátlanul, de most nem ez a lényeg gyerekek. Kurva hálás dolog manapság moziba járni.
